<br>
Sorry, that's a false assumption.  Run your resists over 300 (or 255, if you still buy the rollover theory), you will still take AE damage.  On averange, you will take a full hit about every fifth or sixth blast.  Verant has tuned dragon AE to the point that more than minimals resists are generally a waste of time.<br>
<br>
<br>
And yes, you could argue that positioning could be better.  It still happens, and druids are the ones who get to try and make the situation work. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uvaaxxvlok.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vaaxx VLok</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/11/02 1:26:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgroverants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=650.topic&index=572>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.blizzard.com/images/war3/units/gargoyle.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Raiding</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Example, Group of casters in HoT, druid is the healer. Incoming mob gets positioned with his head past the blocking wall, and all casters are now taking  AE damage. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
